  "text": "[11] [CITATION_1] estimated the variances of global ISC travel time data and inferred the scale length and strength of mantle heterogeneity based on the raytheoretical interpretation of Gaussian-medium variances. However, not only does wavefront healing result in the reduction in slope but lowers the finite-frequency travel time variances. In Figure 4 we show the variances of the theoretical and measured travel time shifts at every fixed a and L for e = 1% versus the dimensionless distance L/a. The figure also presents the analytical variances of first and second-order ray theoretical and Born theoretical travel time shifts in Gaussian media given by [CITATION_2] and [CITATION_3] , respectively. The likely sampling bias in travel time data at large L due to finite modeling space may cause the numerically-computed variances to fall off from the analytical values at the largest L for a ! 2.25l. Overall, the variances of cross-correlation travel time shifts are comparable to the finite-frequency Born theoretical variances but clearly less than the ray-theoretical ones at large L/a.",
